annotation.TEXT: Man, this dungeon was really short, with only four rooms (unless there's more to it that I'm not aware of).
Bah, stupid Leever that I forgot about!
Yeah, that looked like a pier that I can maybe launch the boat from, but in Zelda 1, you can only launch vertically from certain places.
Link, this isn't a Touhou game, and you're not Luigi from Something else, so you don't have to try to graze stuff.
Fairy count: 4

Yeah, proper use of your shield will be helpful against these projectile-throwing enemies. Just make sure you're facing where the projectile is coming from, and don't be in the middle of swinging your sword or throwing/catching your boomerang, etc.
Ah, the reward I get for clearing out that room is the raft! ...Er, I mean "boat", since that's what this hack calls it, apparently.

Hello, and welcome back to Zelda - Another Evil! Here I am at the start of level 1. Let's see if I can complete this whole dungeon today. (Probably, since the dungeons in this hack are supposedly short.)
Gels have just 1 HP, and even the boomerang can kill them. However, they never drop any items. (If you're able to kill Zols in one hit without them splitting, you can get item drops from them.)
Whoa, what the heck? Those things look glitchy. I wonder what they are...
Mwahaha! Zora is so much easier to defeat now!
DUUUDE!!! Okay, there's that shield I was just talking about, and there's the White Sword as well, and I have enough money to buy both of them!
Okay, we're entering the fifth room of this dungeon, which makes it larger than level 1!
Huh. So, there's another item I gotta obtain before heading in a certain direction. Also, do you mean one of those keys that can open locked doors in dungeons?
Oh, yeah, and last time, just before I ended the episode here, I bought the boomerang and the red potion from a shop at bargain basement prices! Alright, so let's get going already.
Well, I think I'll explore a bit further in this direction.
Well, there's another heart container that wasn't guarded by a boss. Also, I'm surprised I haven't gotten a single bomb drop yet. Goriyas can sometimes give you bombs.

New enemy: Goriyas. They have 3 HP, and their boomerangs deal a full heart of damage if they hit you, but they can be blocked with your shield. Also, oddly, their boomerangs won't hurt you on their return trip.
I don't know why I tried boomeranging Zora there. Even though it would make the "stun" sound effect if it hit, Zora doesn't actually get stunned.

Oh, man. A graveyard, with ghosts! Okay, these are Ghinis, which have a whopping 9 HP and remove a full heart if they hit you. However, they're actually not that big of a threat if you're not careless.
Okay, it doesn't look like any of those gravestones are hiding anything. But, there's 9 more up here to check. Let me deal with the enemies first.
I wonder if that's the entrance to level 2...
DOUBLE KILL!

Whoa, level 5?! Okay, I probably shouldn't be here yet. Maybe I could take it on, but I kinda want to do the dungeons in numerical order in this hack. Also, I might lack an item needed to complete this dungeon right now.
Alright, proceeding to the west from here will take me to territories I haven't explored yet.
Well, I'm guessing that's the key that I was told to obtain.
Alright, I think I'm going to make my way back to that pier now. Also, I'll kill three of the Ghinis here right now so that there'll only be one to begin with on later visits to this screen.
And, once again, I get a clock when there are no enemies left in the room. D'oh.
Okay, there's a cave over here, and Zora seems to be absent from this screen as well. (In the original Zelda, there is at least one screen with water that doesn't have Zora.)
Fairy count: 3
Okay, I can go either east or west here. I guess I'll try going east first.

Whoa, that's a lot of Stalfos. Sometimes, you can use the terrain to your advantage. For instance, Link can overlap the bottom half of a block, since he's technically standing on the tile below it, but that'll allow him to strike enemies just above the block safely.
Pointless clock count: 1

...What?! A heart container already?! Okay, I know there were eight Stalfos in this room, but I'd hardly consider that a boss battle... (But, maybe I would if this was the Second Quest, where Stalfos become much more dangerous, with the ability to throw their swords!)
Meh, Zora's not worth the trouble.
Man, those Red Tektites are hard to target sometimes.
I kinda want to murder that Zora, but... meh. Let's check out this cave.
Now, I have a choice of paths here, which automatically makes this dungeon more complex than level 1! I guess I'll go left first.
Ah, there's the pier that I need the raft/boat for. Also, for some reason, there's no Zora on this screen.

Ah, I see. Okay, those glitchy things are apparently Zols, which have 2 HP, and deal a full heart of damage if they hit you. Also, if you don't defeat them in one hit, they split into two Gels, which are these enemies that look like Hershey's Kisses.

Now, in the original Zelda, there were a couple of particular gravestones that could be shoved up or down, and those graves won't produce ghosts if you touch them until after they're moved, so I'm going to quickly check all of these...
Okay, these guys are new. They're called Ropes. They have only 1 HP, but be careful, because if you get lined up with them horizontally or vertically, they'll make a mad dash towards you!
DOUBLE KILL!
Pointless clock count: 2
DOUBLE KILL!

Huh, I'm surprised we haven't seen these things earlier. They're Keese. They have only 1 HP, and just like the Hershey's Kisses (Gels), the boomerang can kill them. But, also like the Gels, they don't drop items.
Okay, here's some Stalfos. They have 2 HP, and are not really a threat.
Alright, so that was level 1, which only took me two minutes, so let's do some more overworld exploring, and maybe put that "boat" to use!

BTW, in the original Zelda's graveyard, you could destroy the invincible Ghinis, by slaying the single attackable Ghini, which would cause all of the currently summoned Ghinis to perish. But, I doubt that'll work here.
Okay, to ride the raft... er, boat, just step onto the pier, and it'll launch automatically.
Also, this room has a really unusual color palette.

White Sword get! In the original Zelda, you had to go to a certain place to find the White Sword, and you needed to have at least 5 heart containers (including the 3 you start with) in order to be allowed to wield it.
"Tick." Graze +1.
Also, it didn't end with a Triforce piece. But, maybe this hack doesn't have Triforce pieces...
Also, as you've seen me do already, you can use the boomerang to collect far away items, which is really handy.
BTW, when facing an enemy that uses straight projectiles like these, if you stand a half-tile to the right of their vertical line, their vertical projectiles will miss you.
Perfect. I doubt I'll ever enter that screen again, but leaving just one Peahat alive there is ideal in case I do return for some reason (like if it turns out that there's more to level 1).
Their 9 HP means that they take quite a pounding to defeat, though. Also, be careful around the gravestones, as touching them will summon a different kind of Ghini that you can't hit.

Whoa, those things respawned quickly. I think it's because those are red Keese, which normally only come from a bigger enemy, which we have yet to see. They're identical to blue Keese, except they'll always respawn after you leave the room and return, even if you only kill some of them.
I was hoping to get a couple of hearts or a fairy from those guys.

Man, seeing this green bush pattern makes me wish I had a candle to burn the SW one to find a secret stairway. If I find a candle later, I've gotta remember to come back here to see if there actually is a secret there.

While an enemy is stunned, you can walk over it safely, but for some reason, as I just demonstrated there, if you kill a stunned enemy while you're overlapping it, it'll hit you, so try to avoid letting that happen.
There we go. Ooh, a fairy that I don't need.
Also, I'm flashing because I picked up a clock from one of the defeated Stalfos. It freezes all on screen enemies and makes you practically invincible until you leave the room.
So, it looks like this was just a five-room dungeon, which resembles a flipped and rotated F-pentomino.
Alright, nothing in those graves. Let's see what's in this cave, after I finish beating up this Ghini.
Ow! I was in the middle of a sword swing there, and got thwacked. Yeah, they toss their boomerangs suddenly without warning, so watch out.
Fortunately, I didn't actually have to kill them again to get out of there.
Okay, I've bought the Magical Shield. Now for the White Sword... (Yeah, you have to leave and reenter the shop in order to buy multiple things.)
MEGA KILL!
And, just like level 1, this only took me a couple minutes. I guess I can look around the overworld a little more before ending the episode.
(But, maybe there's a bomb-able or walk-through-able wall in this dungeon, which might lead to a Triforce piece, but I'm not going to bother checking right now.)
Well, I'm gonna take a look around down here first before I ride my boat.
Oh, and this is what the boomerang does to most enemies. It stuns them for a few seconds, but doesn't actually deal damage.

Bah. My shield is not capable of blocking Zora's shot. There is a bigger shield that can block it, which I have yet to find in this hack. In the original Zelda, you can buy it at most shops at varying prices (with the cheapest one costing 90 rupees).
Yep, it's level 2! Now, I could stop the video here, but if this is anywhere near as short as level 1, I should be able to fit it into this episode.
I think I'll bring the Peahat population on this screen down to one as well.
Well, let's see what's to the right now. Also, this dungeon has a rather interesting color palette, which I think is neat-looking.
DOUBLE KILL!

Alright, let's try out this new equipment! The Magical Shield can block most stronger projectiles, such as Zora's shot. And, the White Sword is twice as powerful as the Wooden Sword, so I can kill 2-HP enemies like these guys in one hit now!

I'd show you the map and my stats, but the subscreen doesn't show a map while you're outdoors. Instead, it shows your Triforce pieces, although I haven't gotten any yet. I wonder if there are any in this hack... Well, until next time, folks. To be continued... Yo!
Also, never touch a gravestone from the south, or you will instantly take a hit from the summoned Ghini, since you'll be overlapping it immediately.

Nuts, still no bomb drops. Alright, let's check all of these gravestones now. Oh, and unlike the Ghinis that you can attack, these invincible ones can move diagonally and can fly over any terrain, so be careful.
Alright, I think this Zora-less screen is a good place to end the episode. I accomplished quite a bit today.
We've got a couple of new enemies here: Orange and Green Moblins. The orange ones have 2 HP, and the green ones have 3 HP. Also, it's possible to get bombs from Green Moblins.
You can return to the pier by just going back the way you came. Very simple.

Whoa, more glitchy Zols, I take it. Also, there's a new enemy here... Bubbles, which are those flashing circular things. They are invincible, but they won't harm your life meter. However, if they hit you, you will be unable to swing your sword for a few seconds.
Leaving the screen makes all of the gravestone-summoned Ghinis despawn.
